<ul class="talks">
  <li>
    <span class="info date"><b>Feb 4</b>3:15-5:15pm</span>
    <span class="info location"><b>SC 232</b>Harvard</span>
    <span class="speaker">Alex Perry</span>
    <br/>
    <span class="title">
      Derived categories of Fano varieties of degree 10
    </span>
    <span class="abstract">
      <span>
In the first half of the talk, 
I'll discuss background material on homological projective duality.
In the second half, 
I'll discuss joint work with Alexander Kuznetsov on the derived categories 
of Fano varieties of Picard number 1, degree 10, and coindex 3.
      </span>
    </span>
  </li>

  <li>
    <span class="info date"><b>Feb 11</b>2015</span>
    <span class="info location"><b>SC 232</b>Harvard</span>
    <span class="speaker">Chi-Yun Hsu</span>
    <br/>
    <span class="title">An Adelic Approach to Riemann-Roch Theorem for Curves over Finite Fields</span>
    <span class="abstract">
      <span>
For curves defined over finite fields, 
we present a proof for the Riemann-Roch theorem
focusing on the their function fields. 
Using the correspondence between adeles and divisors, 
the Riemann-Roch Theorem is a reinterpretation of the self-duality 
of the locally compact additive group of the Adele ring. 
The reference for the talk is A. Weil, Basic Number Theory, chap. VI.  
      </span>
    </span>
  </li>

  <li>
    <span class="info date"><b>Feb 18</b>2015</span>
    <span class="info location"><b>SC 232</b>Harvard</span>
    <span class="speaker">Gabriel Bujokas</span>
    <br/>
    <span class="title">Invariants of branched covers of P^1</span>
    <span class="abstract">
      <span>
A branched cover is a (non-constant) holomorphic map from a smooth irreducible curve C to P^1. If you have spent some time with Anand, you may have heard of some natural vector bundles one can associate to a branched cover. In this talk we will define these vector bundles, and compute their splitting types in some of the known cases.
Depending on how far we get, we may also talk about balanced bundles on a chain of rational curves, and a specific version of the maximal rank problem that arises from these computations.  
      </span>
    </span>
  </li>

  <li>
    <span class="info date"><b>Feb 25</b>2015</span>
    <span class="info location"><b>SC 232</b>Harvard</span>
    <span class="speaker">Atanas Atanasov</span>
    <br/>
    <span class="title">The ADE classification and beyond</span>
    <span class="abstract">
      <span>
The aim of this talk will be to introduce rational double point singularities on surfaces and discuss various aspects of their classification. As time permits, we will motivate several related local-to-global questions about quotient singularities and talk about potential approaches.  
      </span>
    </span>
  </li>

  <li>
    <span class="info date"><b>Mar 4</b>2015</span>
    <span class="info location"><b>SC 232</b>Harvard</span>
    <span class="speaker">C&eacute;sar Lozano Huerta</span>
    <br/>
    <span class="title">Degenerations of Castelnuovo curves in projective 3-space</span>
    <span class="abstract">
      <span>
In this talk, we'll study the following classical question: In what ways can a smooth non-degenerate curve in projective 3-space degenerate to a singular, reducible or non-reduced curve? and as it degenerates, what is the behavior of the defining equations? 
I will present a partial answer to this question for the case of Castelnuovo curves. All the necessary definitions and conventions will be presented.   
      </span>
    </span>
  </li>

  <li>
    <span class="info date"><b>Mar 11</b>2015</span>
    <span class="info location"><b>SC 232</b>Harvard</span>
    <span class="speaker">Francesco Cavazzani</span>
    <br/>
    <span class="title">3264, again?!</span>
    <span class="abstract">
      <span>
How many plane conics are tangent to 5 general conics? Looking back in my 4 years of graduate school, I believe I have explored all possible ways to answer to this question. Still, in this talk I am going to present a different one, using tools from representation theory to deal with the intersection theory of the space of complete conics. As Joe says, the main point of enumerative geometry is not really to get numbers (even though you have to admit that 3264 is a pretty cool number); the aim is to learn how to use new tools, to apply elsewhere. In fact, if time permits, I will show how in my thesis I am trying to apply all of this to the study of the geometry of twisted cubics.  
      </span>
    </span>
  </li>

  <li>
    <span class="info date"><b>Mar 18</b>2015</span>
    <span class="info location"><b>SC 232</b>Harvard</span>
    <span class="speaker">Spring Break -- No seminar</span>
    <br/>
    <span class="title"></span>
