  </li>

  <li>
    <span class="info date"><b>Apr 1</b>2015</span>
    <span class="info location"><b>SC 232</b>Harvard</span>
    <span class="speaker">Erick Knight</span>
    <br/>
    <span class="title">N&eacuteron Models, Elliptic Surfaces, and ADE Singularities</span>
    <span class="abstract">
      <span>
The theory of N&eacuteron models explains how to extend an elliptic curve over the generic fiber of a discrete valuation ring to a relative curve over the whole discrete valuation ring.  The theory is useful to number theorists who can use it to talk about the reduction of an elliptic curve mod p and to algebraic geometers who can use it to give a canonical model of an elliptic surface.  The possible fibers are somewhat mysterious however, and the aim of this talk is to relate them to ADE singularities, which locally look like quotients of the plane by finite subgroups of SL<sub>2</sub>.     
      </span>
    </span>
  </li>

  <li>
    <span class="info date"><b>Apr 8</b>2015</span>
    <span class="info location"><b>SC 232</b>Harvard</span>
    <span class="speaker">Netanel Blaier (MIT) </span>
    <br/>
    <span class="title">Vector bundles on curves in g=0,1</span>
    <span class="abstract">
      <span>
The moduli of vector bundles on a curve is a fascinating mathematical object connected to algebraic geometery, differential geometry and low dimensional topology, but there are only a few cases where vector bundles are classified explicitly. The first nontrivial case (due to Grothendieck's splitting) is when the base curve is elliptic over an algebrically closed field, which was completely solved by Atiyah. This talk would give an overview of some of these classical results.  
      </span>
    </span>
  </li>

  <li class>
    <span class="info date"><b>Apr 15</b>2015</span>
    <span class="info location"><b>SC 232</b>Harvard</span>
    <span class="speaker">Eric Riedl (4:00-5:00pm)</span>
    <br/>
    <span class="title">Unirationality of high dimensional hypersurfaces</span>
    <span class="abstract">
      <span>
One important question in binational geometry is whether a given variety admits a rational map from P<sup>n</sup>. We present a result of Harris, Mazur and Pandharipande that shows that a smooth low degree hypersurface in very high dimension does admit such a rational map.       
      </span>
    </span>
  </li>

  <li>
    <span class="info date"><b>Apr 22</b>2015</span>
    <span class="info location"><b>SC 232</b>Harvard</span>
    <span class="speaker">Changho Han</span>
    <br/>
    <span class="title">Potential density of quartic threefolds</span>
    <span class="abstract">
      <span>
For curves, we know well that how many rational points are there depending on their genus. For surfaces, we have good idea about this problem via Enriques-Kodiara classification. Unfortunately, we do not have much idea for threefolds. Inspired from Lang's conjectures, I will discuss about potential density conjecture, which states that for any projective fano variety over a number field, we can choose some finite extension of that field to extract Zariski dense amount of rational points. This talk will focus on one nontrivial case of this conjecture, the quartic threefolds. I will draw some striking geometrical method used to prove arithmetic fact. The reference for the brilliant idea came from a paper by J. Harris and Y. Tschinkel called "Rational Points on Quartics"       
      </span>
    </span>
  </li>

  <li>
    <span class="info date"><b>Apr 29</b>2015</span>
    <span class="info location"><b>SC 232</b>Harvard</span>
    <span class="speaker">Yaim Cooper</span>
    <br/>
    <span class="title">Severi degrees and representation theory</span>
    <span class="abstract">
      <span>
How many curves are there in P<sup>2</sup> of degree d and genus g
through 3d+g-1 general points?  Mathematicians have been trying to
answer this question for hundreds of years.  In the 90's, Caparaso and
Harris proved a recursive formula which provided a complete answer to
this question.  In this talk, I discuss a new approach to computing
Severi degrees of surfaces in terms of operators on an infinite
dimensional vector space.       
      </span>
    </span>
  </li>

  <li class="next">
    <span class="info date"><b>May 1</b>
<font color="#FF0000">1:30-2:30pm</font></span>
    <span class="info location"><b>SC 232</b>Harvard</span>
    <span class="speaker">Adrian Zahariuc 
<font color="#FF0000">(Friday!)</font></span>
    <br/>
    <span class="title">Specialization of quintic threefolds to the secant variety</span>
    <span class="abstract">
      <span>
We consider the degeneration of quintic threefolds obtained by
running semistable reduction on a general pencil of quintics specializing to the secant variety of a normal elliptic curve in projective 4-space. The question we would like to address is: what are the flat limits of the rational curves in this degeneration? In this talk, I will provide a good âfirst approximationâ to the answer by describing the space of genus zero stable morphisms to the central fiber (as defined by J. Li).       
      </span>
    </span>
  </li>

</ul>

